%N A387890 First difference of consecutive even perfect powers (no perfect power between them).
%C A387890 The minimum descent value a(n)>a(n+1) is conjectured to be 8, as in Pillai's Conjecture.
%H A387890 Gergely Földvári, <a href="https://www.grego.hu/Grego.Coefficial.Divisibility.pdf">Coefficial Divisibility</a> (with terms up to the first 1000 perfect powers).
%H A387890 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PillaisConjecture.html">Pillai's Conjecture</a>
%e A387890 The first pair of consecutive even perfect powers (no perfect power in between) are 4 and 8, their difference (8-4=4) gives the first term of the integer sequence, 4.
%e A387890 The second pair is 32 and 36, their difference (36-32=4) gives the second term of the integer sequence which is also 4.
%o A387890 (Python)
%o A387890 from math import isqrt
%o A387890 def even_pp_diffs(n):
%o A387890     p = {1}
%o A387890     for a in range(2, isqrt(n)+1):
%o A387890         x = a * a
%o A387890         while x <= n:
%o A387890             p.add(x)
%o A387890             x *= a
%o A387890     p = sorted(p)
%o A387890     return [p[i+1] - p[i] for i in range(len(p)-1) if p[i] % 2 == 0 and p[i+1] % 2 == 0]
%o A387890 print(even_pp_diffs(2 * 10**6))
